        "last_activity_date": 1410282770,
        "creation_date": 1410282023,
        "answer_count": 2,
        "title": "What are the benefits of using Generics?",
        "body": "<p>I am new to Generics in Java. I have few doubts about the benefits of using Generics.\nPlease refer the below code - <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>&lt;T extends Bounceable&gt; void goGreen(T ob);\n\nvoid goGreen(Bounceable ob);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Here Bounceable is an interface.<\/p>\n\n<p>Can someone please explain me what is the difference in the above definitions. They both restrict the caller from passing an object to it which is not Bounceable type. If it is possible to implement the same code in interface style, then what is the benefit of using Generics? Thanks in advance.<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 25750193,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "generics"
        ],
        "score": 0,
        "accepted_answer_id": 25750245,
        "closed_reason": "Duplicate",
