    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/39612f829c85ebe7aa40c99966e4d724?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1417953,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1343161,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1343161/keppil",
                "reputation": 46327,
                "display_name": "Keppil",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 6,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1410282770,
            "creation_date": 1410282233,
            "body": "<p>If you are returning nothing like in your example, you haven't gained anything by using generics. The other declaration is just as useful.  <\/p>\n\n<p>On the other hand, generics allow you to create the following method:  <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>&lt;T extends Bounceable&gt; T goGreen(T ob);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This returns an object of the same type as you pass in, which in a lot of scenarios save you a cast.<br>\nTo quote @LuiggiMendoza's excellent example from the comments:<br>\n<em>Assume you have <code>Ball implements Bounceable<\/code> and <code>Cellphone implements Bounceable<\/code>. When you pass a <code>Ball<\/code> to this method, you expect the method to return a <code>Ball<\/code>, not a <code>Cellphone<\/code>.<\/em><\/p>\n\n<p>This is just not possible to achieve with the non-generic approach.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 25750245,
            "question_id": 25750193,
            "last_edit_date": 1410282770
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef0443f6d7ae8a1c5471a0f7a843e2b0?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 4187371,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3430807,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3430807/andreas",
                "reputation": 5156,
                "display_name": "Andreas",
                "accept_rate": 60
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1410282763,
            "creation_date": 1410282763,
            "body": "<p>What if you wanted it to return the same type it took in?<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>class Ball implements Bounceable{\n   void throw(Object target){\n      //impl\n   }   \n}\n\nBounceable goGreen(Bounceable ob);//returns a Bounceable back. no throw method\n\n&lt;T extends Bounceable&gt; T goGreen(T ob);//returns a ball back when called with ball. I can throw it!\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>What if you wanted to restrict the types the other way?<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>&lt;T super Bounceable&gt; void setBounceableParent(T ob);//not possible with just polymorphism \n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>What if you wanted a class that worked on a any type?<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>class Holder&lt;T&gt;{\n   T data; \n   void put(T newData){\n      data=newData;\n   }\n   T get(){//how do you make this type safe without generics or duck typing?\n      return data;\n   } \n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 25750381,
            "question_id": 25750193
        }
    ],
